// TEST: Physics -- Spectral Persistence: Torus vs Chaos on Real Trajectories
import ppl as ppl
// ============================================================================
// The polyspectra arc's verdict -- integrable systems have DISCRETE spectra
// (autocovariance persists), chaotic ones CONTINUOUS (it decays) -- computed
// through the Blade tower on real Henon-Heiles trajectories, one former call
// per system. Both trajectories share the same Hamiltonian; only the energy
// differs: REGULAR at E = 0.0185 lives on a KAM 2-torus (its second
// invariant EXISTS but is non-polynomial -- exactly the class the degree-4
// null space of example 14 is blind to), CHAOTIC at E = 0.153 (just under
// the escape energy 1/6) is mixing. NOTE: at E ~ 0.13 many HH trajectories
// are STICKY (mixed phase space); the chaotic IC here was verified to mix.
// The data are STRIDED pair samples: row k = u(t_i + tau_k) at every 10th
// sample, so 310-value rows span the full 800-time-unit series and the
// covariance of row 0 with row k estimates C(tau_k) at full statistical
// power (tau = 0, 160, 168, 176; u = x + 0.7 y). cumulants(.,2) on the
// like Idx<4> array returns the whole lag battery in one call; persistence
// = RMS of the three long-lag covariances over C(0). The three lags spread
// across more than one oscillation period, so the read is not phase-fragile.
// Verdict: PERSISTS (0.78, the torus -- a second invariant exists, whether
// or not any polynomial dictionary can spell it) vs DECAYS (0.06, mixing).
// tools/spectral_quadrature.ps1 goes further on the same machinery: the
// lagged tower is a CHEBYSHEV MOMENT SEQUENCE of the spectral measure, and
// Gauss quadrature on it extracts the torus's two fundamental frequencies.
// ============================================================================
type TimeIdx = Idx<310>
